This is doable in D3, just add another `rect` after your main rectangle for nodes.

You need to add the rectangle in your D3 code like the following.

```javascript
// Draw the rectangle person boxes
node.append(&quot;rect&quot;)
  .attr({
    x: -(boxWidth/2),
    y: -(boxHeight/2),
    width: boxWidth,
    height: boxHeight
  });

  // ***** Add the following here *****
  // This assumes your progress bar has boxWidth as its full width,
  // starts from the left, and has the height as the entire box.
  // To change this behavior, adjust the corresponding lines (x, y, width and height).
  node.append(&#39;rect&#39;)
    .attr(&#39;class&#39;, &#39;progressBar&#39;)
    .attr(&#39;x&#39;, -(boxWidth/2))
    .attr(&#39;y&#39;, -(boxHeight/2))
    .attr(&#39;width&#39;, d =&gt; parseInt(d.progress.split(&#39;|&#39;)[1].trim()) / 100 * boxWidth)
    .attr(&#39;height&#39;, boxHeight);
```

You can also add styling in your CSS:
```css
.person rect {
  fill: #fff;
  stroke: steelblue;
  stroke-width: 1px;
}
/* ***** Add the following here, adjust as needed ***** */
.person rect.progressBar {
  fill: steelblue;
}
```

The mouse hovering part is a little bit tricky as you may want to add `:hover` to the `&lt;g&gt;` element. And you&#39;ll need to [make pointer events to pass through everything inside the node][1] (unless you want to do something fancy to the node itself, this shouldn&#39;t be a big issue). Then the CSS part becomes the following:

```css
.person rect {
  fill: #fff;
  stroke: steelblue;
  stroke-width: 1px;
}
/* ***** Add the following here, adjust as needed ***** */
.person rect.progressBar {
  fill: steelblue;
  visibility: hidden;
}

.person * {
  pointer-events: none;
}

.person:hover rect.progressBar {
  visibility: visible;
}}

/** 
 * Also change the following
 * Because if everything in &lt;g&gt; has pointer-events bypassed,
 * it will not trigger hover by default.
 */
.person {
  pointer-events: bounding-box;
  font: 14px sans-serif;
}
```


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/9738984/css-hover-passes-through-elements-to-activate-hover-on-covered-element

